{"title_page": "Ancol Dreamland", "text_new": "{{Infobox company|\n| name   = PT Pembangunan Jaya Ancol Tbk\n| logo   = \n| type   = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{idx|PJAA}}\n| foundation     = 1966\n| location       = Head Office Jl. Lodan Timur 7 Jakarta [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n| key_people     = C. Paul Tehusijarana ([[CEO]]), Honggo Widjojo Kangmasto ([[Komisaris Utama]])\n| industry       = Tourism & Property Management\n| products       = Recreations Place, and Property\n| owner          = [[Jakarta|Government of Jakarta]] (72%)<br>PT Pembangunan Jaya (18%)<br>Public float (10%)<ref>[http://www.ancol.com/infokorporat ''Info Korporat PT Pembangunan Jaya Ancol'', retrieved form ancol.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423190022/http://www.ancol.com/infokorporat |date=April 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n| revenue        = {{profit}} [[Indonesian Rupiah|Rp]] 1.28&nbsp;trillion (2016)\n| equity         = {{profit}} Rp 1.828&nbsp;trillion (2016)\n| assets         = {{profit}} Rp 3.769&nbsp;trillion (2016)\n| net_income     = {{profit}} [[Indonesian Rupiah|Rp]] 131&nbsp;billion (2016)\n| num_employees    = 781 <small>(2016)</small>\n| homepage       = [http://www.ancol.com www.ancol.com]\n}}\n{{maplink|frame=yes|frame-width=230|zoom=15|type=point}}\n{{Coord|-6.122743|106.831529|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n'''Taman Impian Jaya Ancol''' otherwise known as '''Ancol Dreamland''' is an integral part of Ancol Bay City, a [[resort]] destination located along [[Jakarta]]'s waterfront, in [[Ancol]] ([[Kelurahan]]), [[Pademangan]], Indonesia.\n\nIt is owned by PT. Pembangunan Jaya Ancol Tbk, a subsidiary of Pembangunan Jaya Group. Ancol Dreamland opened in 1966 and is currently the largest integrated tourism area in South East Asia, boasting an international championship [[golf course]], a [[theme park]], hotels and other recreational facilities.\n\n==History==\nBefore Ancol Dreamland, Ancol was a mosquito-infested swamps and fish ponds, and the source of century-old malaria outbreak in Batavia. The idea to convert the marshy area of Ancol into Jakarta's largest entertainment center, with housing and industrial estates adjoining it, was proposed by President [[Sukarno]] in the early 1960s. The idea opposed the initial idea to convert the area of Ancol into a purely industrial area.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015|p=25}}\n\nDevelopment of Ancol was started during the tenure of [[Ali Sadikin]], the governor of Jakarta in 1966. The entertainment complex was named ''Taman Impian Jaya Ancol'' or Ancol Dreamland. The first facility was the Bina Ria Ancol beach, best known for its [[drive-in theater]] especially during the 1970s, then followed with a golf course, swimming pool, oceanarium, Putri Duyung cottage, Hotel Horison and its casino.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015|p=25}}  The ''Dunia Fantasi'' (Fantasy World) theme park was built in 1984.\n\n==Entertainment and amusement parks==\nToday, the 552&nbsp;hectare recreation area is known as the Ancol Jakarta Bay City, contains hotels, cottages, beaches, a theme park, traditional market places, an oceanarium, a golf field and marina.\n\n===Dunia Fantasi (Fantasy World)===\n[[File:Dunia Fantasi Ancol.JPG|thumb|right|Fantasy World]]\n[[File:Zamperla Backflash.jpg|thumb|right|''Tornado'' at Dunia Fantasi (Fantasy World)]]\nDunia Fantasi (often shortened to \"Dufan\") is Jakarta's own theme park complete with over 40 rides and attractions. It is located in North Jakarta, facing the Java Sea.<ref>http://www.jakarta-tourism.go.id/content/taman-impian-jaya-ancol</ref> The theme park is divided into eight regions which are Jakarta, Indonesia, Asia, Africa, America, Europe, and Fantasi Hikayat (Legendary Fantasy) region featuring [[Ancient Greece]] and [[Ancient Egypt]] architecture. The theme park complies with international standards through ISO 9001:2000 certification. Admission to Dunia Fantasi is chargeable at around Rp 295.000 from Mondays to Fridays, and Rp 325.000 on Saturday, Sundays and public holidays.<ref>https://www.ancol.com/id/tiket/</ref> It is considered as Jakarta's largest and most interesting recreation park, and located on reclaimed land at the Bay of Jakarta. According to the Jakarta Tourism & Culture Office website, other attractions within include the Art Market, an Eco-Park and an Ocean Park. In the district of Ancol where Dunia Fantasi is located, it is a common getaway for tourists and locals alike, away from the hustle and bustle of the city.<ref>http://www.jakarta-tourism.go.id/content/taman-impian-jaya-ancol</ref>\n\nAmong its most popular attractions are Halilintar (a [[roller coaster]] manufactured by [[Arrow Dynamics]]), Niagara-gara (a [[log flume]]), Istana Boneka (a local version of Disney's [[It's a Small World]]) and Balada Kera (Monkey Parody \u2013 animatronics show) Theater show. Other attractions include Bianglala ([[ferris wheel]]), Kora-Kora ([[Pirate ship (ride)|swinging ship]]), Poci-Poci (spinning cups ride),Kereta Misteri (a [[indoor roller coaster]] manufactured by [[Intamin Rides]]), and Hysteria ([[drop tower]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancol.com/maps/duniafantasy/duniafantasy.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229001445/http://www.ancol.com/maps/duniafantasy/duniafantasy.php |archivedate=2008-12-29 }} Dunia Fantasy</ref>\n\nSeveral of the latest and newest rides are Kicir-Kicir ([[Power Surge (ride)|Power Surge]]) (2004), [[Perang Bintang]] (Star Wars) (2005) - an interactive dark ride, Meteor Attack (2006) and Tornado (Windshear by [[Zamperla]]) (2007). Some seasonal attractions include Le Belles cabaret show, Russian Circus and Euro Kids Circus.\n\nA former Show Building that used to house the Rama Shita: Legend Of The Future ride was burned in 2004 and then converted into a large indoor exhibition hall, occasionally hosting special shows. Then in 2014 is reimagined into Indoor Dufan Section that contain Ice Age: Sid's Tour, Kontiki, Hello Kitty Adventure (Rumored will be replaced).\n\nSince June 21, 2011 Dunia Fantasi (Dufan) will open Kalila Adventure [[Animatronic]] Theater which is the most complete in the world. The theme stories are about Beautiful Indonesia. Then in 2018 Kalila Section is closed to make way the expansion of America Section in the park that contain the biggest indoor coaster in Indonesia themed to America on the 19th Century that will tell the story of the Werewolf that lived in the house.<ref>[http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/148784 Kalila Adventure Animatronic Theater]</ref>\n\nOn March 2019 the park has announced a new area set to open mid to late 2019 with 9 new attractions: Baling Baling (a [[Zierer]] Star Shape, also the first in Asia), Paralayang (an [[SBF Visa Group]] Airborne Shot), Turbo Drop (an [[SBF Visa Group]] Drop'n Twist), Fantastique 2.0 (Delay until further notice), Kereta Misteri (a werewolf themed indoor tracked ride from an Intamin Manufacter), Karavel, Kolibri, Zig Zag and Ontang Anting.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFHrFfdPCeo</ref>\n\n===Atlantis Water Adventure===\nAtlantis Water Adventure was built on the former site of Gelanggang Renang (Swimming Courtyard). Occupying over five hectares of land, this [[water park]] is themed on the mythological underwater world of [[Atlantis]]. Its facilities include a wave pool, continuous flowing river pool, rainbow ball pool, waterfall pool, several slides, two children's pools, five restaurants, and a food court that was imported from India, Brazil, Spain, Bangladesh. A volleyball court and event center are also available to accommodate the needs of visitors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancol.com/maps/gelanggangrenang/gelanggangrenang.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222235439/http://www.ancol.com/maps/gelanggangrenang/gelanggangrenang.php |archivedate=2008-02-22 }} Atlantis Water Adventure</ref>\n\n===Ocean Dream Samudra===\n[[File:Dolphin show - ancol (jakarta, indonesia 1995) (3).jpg|thumb|right|Dolphin show]]\nOcean Dream Samudra features several animal shows, a small aquarium, and a 4D theater. The trained animal shows include a [[dolphin]] show and [[sea lion]] show. The 4D theater projects 3D image movies with sensations such as cool breezes and water sprays located inside a large building with [[Mesoamerican pyramid]] theme. On 2011 Ocean Dream Samudra will be revitalized with the budget Rp.27 billion ($3.1 million). Ocean Dream Samudra now holds the \"Under the Sea Musical Dance\" attraction at Underwater Theater.\n\n====Dolphin exhibit====\n*[[Bottlenose dolphin]]\n\n====Sea Lion exhibit====\n*[[South American sea lion]]\n\n====Sea Lion show====\n*[[Asian small-clawed otter]]\n*[[South American fur seal]]\n\n====Koi aquarium====\n*[[Koi]]\n*[[Flowerhorn cichlid]]\n\n====Rumah Pintar (Library and museum)====\n*[[Flowerhorn cichlid]]\n*[[Oscar cichlid]]\n*[[Silver arowana]] (Preserved)\n*[[Pufferfish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Bowmouth Guitarfish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Porcupinefish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Blacktip reef shark]] (Preserved)\n*[[Orange-spotted grouper]] (Preserved)\n*[[Asian small-clawed otter]] (3 pups, preserved)\n*[[Bala shark]] (Preserved)\n*[[Bottlenose dolphin]] (3 calfs, preserved)\n*[[Ribbon eel]] (Preserved)\n*[[Clown featherback]] (Preserved)\n*[[South American sea lion]] (Pup, preserved)\n*[[Coral catshark]] (Preserved)\n*[[Walking catfish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Iridescent shark]] (Preserved)\n\n====Aviary====\n*[[Sun conure]]\n*[[Scarlet macaw]]\n*[[Green winged macaw]]\n*[[Blue-and-yellow macaw]]\n*[[Yellow-crested cockatoo]]\n*[[White cockatoo]]\n*[[Javan peafowl]]\n*[[Brahminy kite]]\n*[[White-bellied sea eagle]]\n\n====Tortoise exhibit====\n*[[Asian forest tortoise]]\n\n====Duck Pond====\n*[[American Pekin]]\n*[[Swedish Blue]]\n*[[Chinese goose]] (white)\n\n====Penguin Kingdom====\n*[[Humboldt penguin]]\n*[[Blacktip reef shark]]\n*[[Coral catshark]]\n*[[Protoreaster nodosus]]\n\n====Former animals====\n*[[Hippopotamus]] (To Ming Tse) \n*[[Sun bear]]\n*[[Asian water monitor]]\n*[[Bali duck]]\n*[[Australian pelican]]\n*[[Milkfish]]\n*[[Beluga whale]]\n\n===Sea World Ancol===\n{{See also|Sea World Jakarta}} \nSeaWorld Ancol was the largest oceanarium in South East Asia at the time it was opened, in 1996, as SeaWorld Jakarta. It was owned by [[Lippo Group]] until 2014, when contract problems caused it to be owned by Jaya Ancol now. It features the acclaimed Antasena tunnel as well as the sea friends pool, main pool, alligator pool, and shark pool.<ref>http://www.seaworldindonesia.com SeaWorld Indonesia</ref> Despite its name, it is completely unaffiliated with the US-based [[SeaWorld Parks & Entertainment]] and their parks in Orlando, San Antonio, and San Diego.<ref>http://seaworldparks.com {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413191552/http://seaworldparks.com/ |date=2014-04-13 }}</ref>\n\n===Beaches===\n[[File:Festival beach Ancol Jakarta.jpg|thumb|right|Festival Beach]]\nThere are two main beaches within the resort, the Carnival and Festival beach.  British band [[Iron Maiden]] has played for the first time in Indonesia on 17 February 2011 at the Carnival Beach site, to over 25,000 strong crowd.<ref>[http://ironmaidenflight666.blogspot.com/2011/02/jakarta-setlist-final-frontier-tour.html BLOG FLIGHT 666 - IRON MAIDEN BRASIL: Jakarta: Setlist The Final Frontier Tour 2011<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Pasar Seni===\nPasar Seni is an Art Market that started over 25 years ago. .  It has become a center for handicrafts and art products. This art market has an open state, plaza, and souvenir shops. Pasar Seni has also become a center where artists would create and sell their products. Every Friday night at 8:30 pm, Pasar Seni Ancol organized the event named \"New Friday Jazz Nite\".\n\n===Executive Golf Fun===\n[[File:Arapaima gigas at sea world.JPG|thumb|right|Arapaima fish at Sea World]]\nAncol's Golf Course has recently relaunched as Executive Golf Fun. This is Indonesia\u2019s first international beach golf course with 18 holes spread over an area of 33&nbsp;hectares. The golf course has a pro-shop, an executive room, a meeting hall and restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancol.com/maps/padanggolf/padanggolf.php?action%3Dprofile |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301094330/http://www.ancol.com/maps/padanggolf/padanggolf.php?action=profile |archivedate=2008-03-01 }} Executive Golf Fun</ref>\n\n===Jaya Bowling===\nAncol Dreamland has several facilities for games and entertainment. One of these facilities is Jaya Bowling. This bowling center is the first and largest bowling center in Indonesia. Indonesia's National Bowling Training Center is in Jaya Bowling.\n\n===Allianz Eco Park===\nIt was built in 2011 by PT Global Land Development Tbk with a budget of Rp.15 billion ($1.7 million). This area  consists of 4 themes, Eco Energy, Eco Care, Eco Nature and Eco Art. It once hosted the 2013 [[World Robot Olympiad]] and the finale and result and reunion show of [[Indonesian Idol 2012]].\n\n====Pony ride====\n*[[Pony]]\n\n====Siamang Island====\n*[[Siamang]]\n*[[Koi]]\n\n====Pelican island====\n*[[Australian pelican]]\n\n====Learning Farm====\nThe farm have a hybrid between local duck and muscovy duck, named TikTok.\n*[[Javan rusa]]\n*[[Helmeted guineafowl]]\n*[[Chinese goose]] (White)\n*[[Dutch rabbit]]\n*[[American rabbit]]\n*[[Water buffalo]]\n*[[Honey bee]]\n\n====Turkey island====\n*[[Domesticated turkey]]\n\n====Parrot aviary====\n*[[Black-capped lory]]\n\n====Former animals====\n*[[Red-eared slider]]\n*[[Amboina box turtle]]\n*[[Northern cassowary]] (Moved to Fauna Land)\n*[[Domesticated pigeon]]\n\n===Fauna Land===\nFaunaland is a zoo located inside Allianz Ecopark and stands on an area of \u200b\u200bapproximately 5 hectares consisting of land and water. Faunaland carries the concept of Papua which is a fusion between the continents of Asia and Australia so as to create the beauty of flora, fauna and the cultural arts of the area. This concept presents unique and rare animals from various regions in Indonesia, especially eastern Indonesia and also countries in the world.\n\n====Leopard exhibit====\n*[[Javan leopard]]\n*[[Black panther]] (One individual only have three legs, one of its legs got trapped in pig trap)\n\n====Rare animals area====\n*[[Malayan tapir]]\n*[[Sunda porcupine]]\n\n====Petting zone====\n*[[Donkey]]\n*[[Pony]]\n*[[American Pygmy]]\n*[[Rabbit]]\n\n====Wild cat exhibit====\n*[[Asian golden cat]]\n*[[Sunda clouded leopard]]\n*[[Serval]]\n*[[Twelve-wired bird-of-paradise]]\n*[[Binturong]] (subspecies that came from Java)\n\n====Mini primate exhibits====\n*[[Spectral tarsier]]\n*[[Silvery marmoset]]\n\n====Marsupial exhibits====\n*[[Grizzled tree kangaroo]] (Jacky)\n*[[Banded linsang]]\n*[[Red-necked wallaby]] (Albino)\n\n====Petting zone 2====\n*[[Pony]]\n*[[Donkey]]\n\n====Cassowary exhibit====\n*[[Northern cassowary]]\n\n====White lion exhibit====\n*[[White lion]]\n\n====Tortoise exhibit====\n*[[Aldabra giant tortoise]]\n\n====Pond====\n*[[Amphilophus labiatus]]\n*[[Tilapia]]\n\n====Bird Island====\n*[[Pesquet's parrot]]\n*[[Palm cockatoo]]\n*[[Eclectus parrot]]\n*[[Papuan hornbill]]\n*[[Blue-and-yellow macaw]]\n*[[Green winged macaw]]\n*[[Lesser bird-of-paradise]]\n\n====Bird show====\n*[[Wreathed hornbill]]\n*[[Rhinoceros hornbill]]\n*[[Brahminy kite]]\n*[[Barred eagle owl]] (Ello)\n*[[Spotted wood owl]] (Batara)\n*[[White-bellied sea eagle]]\n*[[Australian pelican]]\n*[[Sunda porcupine]]\n\n====Primate exhibits====\n*[[Black-spotted cuscus]] (Bobba)\n*[[Coconut crab]]\n*[[Proboscis monkey]]\n*[[Crab-eating macaque]] (Albino)\n*[[Siamang]] (The zoo have an albino siamang named Otong, which is the only one in the world)\n\n====Quarantined animals====\n*[[Northern lynx]]\n*[[Black-headed python]]\n*[[Common spotted cuscus]] (Albino)\n\n====Former animals====\n*[[Great grey owl]]\n*[[Australian green tree frog]]\n*[[Mandarin duck]]\n*[[Writhed hornbill]]\n*[[Knobbed hornbill]]\n*[[Lesser flamingo]]\n*[[Javan peafowl]]\n*[[Sunda porcupine]] (Albino)\n\nThe zoo planned to add [[Golden tiger]], [[Crocodile skink]], [[Northern snake-necked turtle]], [[Hyacinth macaw]], [[Sulawesi bear cuscus]], [[Silver pheasant]], [[Cream-coloured giant squirrel]], [[Snowy owl]], and [[Pig-nosed turtle]], but there is no further information.\n\n===Ancol Beach City===\nAncol Beach City is a new Lifestyle & Entertainment Center in Ancol, Jakarta. It was built by PT Wahana Agung Indonesia, a subsidiary of PT Global Land Development Tbk (now MNC Land). There'll be a Madame Tussauds wax Museum, Mata Elang International Stadium Concert Hall with a maximum capacity of 22.000, 77 culinary centre, 42 shops, etc.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120109021154/http://travel.okezone.com/read/2012/01/04/407/551584/ancol-beach-city-alternatif-gaul-anak-muda-jakarta Ancol Beach City, Alternatif Gaul Anak Muda Jakarta<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nAncol Dreamland can easily be reached by car, motorcycle, electric train (KRL), or the [[TransJakarta]] Busway.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120730173834/http://www.beritajakarta.com/2008/en/newsview.aspx?id=12533 Berita Jakarta.com]</ref> Passengers who wants to go to Ancol Dreamland by train can arrive on Kampung Bandan or Ancol Station. Because Ancol Dreamland is so large, effective transportation has been a concern. Some transportation methods around Ancol Dreamland include becak (rickshaw) and other vehicles such as train ride from the east entrance to Carnaval beach, and gondola to help tourists navigate around the area to their next destination. Passengers from Kampung Melayu, Harmoni, and Pusat Grosir Cililitan can use [[Transjakarta|Transjakarta Busway]] to go to Ancol Dreamland.\n\n===Gondola===\n[[File:Cable car Gondola Ancol Jakarta Bay City.jpg|thumb|right|Ancol Gondola]]\nThis is the latest transportation alternative in the area. The Gondola is a skylift cable car system with thirty-seven cars built along the shore of Jakarta's bay. It offers a view of the resort and the sea as well as the city.\n\n==Hotels==\n* [[Putri Duyung Cottage]] is the home of beach cottages with over 137 waterfront rooms. Putri Duyung Cottage is also one of building projects of PT Global Land Development Tbk. \n* [[Mercure Convention Centre]], formerly the Hotel Horison, is a four-star hotel that consists of a hotel tower and large mice facility. The hotel was built in the 1970s as the largest hotel at Ancol. In the 1970s, there was the Copacabana Casino, one of the three legal casinos in Jakarta that were licensed in 1967 by Governor [[Ali Sadikin]] (the others being casinos on [[Jalan M.H. Thamrin|Jalan Thamrin]] and Jalan Hayam Wuruk) in order to raise venture to help fund development of the city's infrastructure. Pressure from religious leaders eventually forced the government to ban all gambling in 1981.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015}}\n* [[Hotel Raddin Ancol]] is an Accor's [[Mercure Hotels|Mercure]] managed hotel located by the side of Dunia Fantasi.\n\n==Residential==\nAncol project also included a residential development to the east of Putri Duyung Cottage developed back in the 1970s. Some of the residential projects were the Ancol Mansion apartment complex.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015}}\n\n==Future developments==\nAncol Taman Impian is planned to be expanded mainly through land reclamation along Jakarta's bay with a land reserve of over eighty hectares. A long-term goal which includes a major expansion of the current Dunia Fantasi theme park as well as the construction of the Marina Sports Centre and Carnival Beach Club. And in this year Ancol is going to Build the Bird Park and the rumored location at Allianz Ecopark.\n\n==Accidents==\nA cement-based decorative wall of a water slide of the Atlantis Water Adventure Park collapsed due to corrosion and made a part of the wall of water slide also collapse in September 25, 2011 injuring four visitors, including a child. The Jakarta Construction Supervision and Regulation Agency said, \"There will be an audit by a consultant before the management is allowed to rebuild the collapsed structure.\" Less than 3 months previously, there was another cement structure that collapsed and in July 2011, fifteen passengers panicked when they were stuck on their seats when the Tornado thrill ride stalled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/09/25/5-injured-atlantis-water-park-accident.html |title=5 injured in Atlantis water park accident |date=September 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002153257/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/09/25/5-injured-atlantis-water-park-accident.html |archivedate=2011-10-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/at-least-2-injured-in-ancol-water-slide-collapse/467576 \n |title=At Least 2 Injured in Ancol Water Slide Collapse \n |date=September 25, 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927142409/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/at-least-2-injured-in-ancol-water-slide-collapse/467576 \n |archivedate=2011-09-27 \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/09/29/atlantis-be-penalized-over-accident.html |title=Atlantis to be penalized over accident |date=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n*[[Ancol]]\n*[[Jakarta]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Cited works==\n*{{cite book |last=Merrillees |first=Scott |date=2015 |title=Jakarta: Portraits of a Capital 1950-1980 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=akLWjgEACAAJ&dq=JAKARTA:+Portraits+of+a+Capital+1950-1980 |location=Jakarta |publisher=Equinox Publishing |isbn=9786028397308  |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ancol Jakarta Bay City}}\n*[http://www.ancol.com Official site]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Indonesia}}\n\n[[Category:Amusement parks in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Parks and lakes in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Animatronic attractions]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1966]]\n[[Category:Venues of the 2018 Asian Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company|\n| name   = PT Pembangunan Jaya Ancol Tbk\n| logo   = \n| type   = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{idx|PJAA}}\n| foundation     = 1966\n| location       = Head Office Jl. Lodan Timur 7 Jakarta [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n| key_people     = C. Paul Tehusijarana ([[CEO]]), Honggo Widjojo Kangmasto ([[Komisaris Utama]])\n| industry       = Tourism & Property Management\n| products       = Recreations Place, and Property\n| owner          = [[Jakarta|Government of Jakarta]] (72%)<br>PT Pembangunan Jaya (18%)<br>Public float (10%)<ref>[http://www.ancol.com/infokorporat ''Info Korporat PT Pembangunan Jaya Ancol'', retrieved form ancol.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423190022/http://www.ancol.com/infokorporat |date=April 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n| revenue        = {{profit}} [[Indonesian Rupiah|Rp]] 1.28&nbsp;trillion (2016)\n| equity         = {{profit}} Rp 1.828&nbsp;trillion (2016)\n| assets         = {{profit}} Rp 3.769&nbsp;trillion (2016)\n| net_income     = {{profit}} [[Indonesian Rupiah|Rp]] 131&nbsp;billion (2016)\n| num_employees    = 781 <small>(2016)</small>\n| homepage       = [http://www.ancol.com www.ancol.com]\n}}\n{{maplink|frame=yes|frame-width=230|zoom=15|type=point}}\n{{Coord|-6.122743|106.831529|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n'''Taman Impian Jaya Ancol''' otherwise known as '''Ancol Dreamland''' is an integral part of Ancol Bay City, a [[resort]] destination located along [[Jakarta]]'s waterfront, in [[Ancol]] ([[Kelurahan]]), [[Pademangan]], Indonesia.\n\nIt is owned by PT. Pembangunan Jaya Ancol Tbk, a subsidiary of Pembangunan Jaya Group. Ancol Dreamland opened in 1966 and is currently the largest integrated tourism area in South East Asia, boasting an international championship [[golf course]], a [[theme park]], hotels and other recreational facilities.\n\n==History==\nBefore Ancol Dreamland, Ancol was a mosquito-infested swamps and fish ponds, and the source of century-old malaria outbreak in Batavia. The idea to convert the marshy area of Ancol into Jakarta's largest entertainment center, with housing and industrial estates adjoining it, was proposed by President [[Sukarno]] in the early 1960s. The idea opposed the initial idea to convert the area of Ancol into a purely industrial area.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015|p=25}}\n\nDevelopment of Ancol was started during the tenure of [[Ali Sadikin]], the governor of Jakarta in 1966. The entertainment complex was named ''Taman Impian Jaya Ancol'' or Ancol Dreamland. The first facility was the Bina Ria Ancol beach, best known for its [[drive-in theater]] especially during the 1970s, then followed with a golf course, swimming pool, oceanarium, Putri Duyung cottage, Hotel Horison and its casino.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015|p=25}}  The ''Dunia Fantasi'' (Fantasy World) theme park was built in 1984.\n\n==Entertainment and amusement parks==\nToday, the 552&nbsp;hectare recreation area is known as the Ancol Jakarta Bay City, contains hotels, cottages, beaches, a theme park, traditional market places, an oceanarium, a golf field and marina.\n\n===Dunia Fantasi (Fantasy World)===\n[[File:Dunia Fantasi Ancol.JPG|thumb|right|Fantasy World]]\n[[File:Zamperla Backflash.jpg|thumb|right|''Tornado'' at Dunia Fantasi (Fantasy World)]]\nDunia Fantasi (often shortened to \"Dufan\") is Jakarta's own theme park complete with over 40 rides and attractions. It is located in North Jakarta, facing the Java Sea.<ref>http://www.jakarta-tourism.go.id/content/taman-impian-jaya-ancol</ref> The theme park is divided into eight regions which are Jakarta, Indonesia, Asia, Africa, America, Europe, and Fantasi Hikayat (Legendary Fantasy) region featuring [[Ancient Greece]] and [[Ancient Egypt]] architecture. The theme park complies with international standards through ISO 9001:2000 certification. Admission to Dunia Fantasi is chargeable at around Rp 295.000 from Mondays to Fridays, and Rp 325.000 on Saturday, Sundays and public holidays.<ref>https://www.ancol.com/id/tiket/</ref> It is considered as Jakarta's largest and most interesting recreation park, and located on reclaimed land at the Bay of Jakarta. According to the Jakarta Tourism & Culture Office website, other attractions within include the Art Market, an Eco-Park and an Ocean Park. In the district of Ancol where Dunia Fantasi is located, it is a common getaway for tourists and locals alike, away from the hustle and bustle of the city.<ref>http://www.jakarta-tourism.go.id/content/taman-impian-jaya-ancol</ref>\n\nAmong its most popular attractions are Halilintar (a [[roller coaster]] manufactured by [[Arrow Dynamics]]), Niagara-gara (a [[log flume]]), Istana Boneka (a local version of Disney's [[It's a Small World]]) and Balada Kera (Monkey Parody \u2013 animatronics show) Theater show. Other attractions include Bianglala ([[ferris wheel]]), Kora-Kora ([[Pirate ship (ride)|swinging ship]]), Poci-Poci (spinning cups ride),Kereta Misteri (a [[indoor roller coaster]] manufactured by [[Intamin Rides]]), and Hysteria ([[drop tower]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancol.com/maps/duniafantasy/duniafantasy.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229001445/http://www.ancol.com/maps/duniafantasy/duniafantasy.php |archivedate=2008-12-29 }} Dunia Fantasy</ref>\n\nSeveral of the latest and newest rides are Kicir-Kicir ([[Power Surge (ride)|Power Surge]]) (2004), [[Perang Bintang]] (Star Wars) (2005) - an interactive dark ride, Meteor Attack (2006) and Tornado (Windshear by [[Zamperla]]) (2007). Some seasonal attractions include Le Belles cabaret show, Russian Circus and Euro Kids Circus.\n\nA former Show Building that used to house the Rama Shita: Legend Of The Future ride was burned in 2004 and then converted into a large indoor exhibition hall, occasionally hosting special shows. Then in 2014 is reimagined into Indoor Dufan Section that contain Ice Age: Sid's Tour, Kontiki, Hello Kitty Adventure (Rumored will be replaced).\n\nSince June 21, 2011 Dunia Fantasi (Dufan) will open Kalila Adventure [[Animatronic]] Theater which is the most complete in the world. The theme stories are about Beautiful Indonesia. Then in 2018 Kalila Section is closed to make way the expansion of America Section in the park that contain the biggest indoor coaster in Indonesia themed to America on the 19th Century that will tell the story of the Werewolf that lived in the house.<ref>[http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/148784 Kalila Adventure Animatronic Theater]</ref>\n\nOn March 2019 the park has announced a new area set to open mid to late 2019 with 9 new attractions: Baling Baling (a [[Zierer]] Star Shape, also the first in Asia), Paralayang (an [[SBF Visa Group]] Airborne Shot), Turbo Drop (an [[SBF Visa Group]] Drop'n Twist), Fantastique 2.0 (Delay until further notice), Kereta Misteri (a werewolf themed indoor tracked ride from an Intamin Manufacter), Karavel, Kolibri, Zig Zag and Ontang Anting.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFHrFfdPCeo</ref>\n\n===Atlantis Water Adventure===\nAtlantis Water Adventure was built on the former site of Gelanggang Renang (Swimming Courtyard). Occupying over five hectares of land, this [[water park]] is themed on the mythological underwater world of [[Atlantis]]. Its facilities include a wave pool, continuous flowing river pool, rainbow ball pool, waterfall pool, several slides, two children's pools, five restaurants, and a food court that was imported from India, Brazil, Spain, Bangladesh. A volleyball court and event center are also available to accommodate the needs of visitors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancol.com/maps/gelanggangrenang/gelanggangrenang.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222235439/http://www.ancol.com/maps/gelanggangrenang/gelanggangrenang.php |archivedate=2008-02-22 }} Atlantis Water Adventure</ref>\n\n===Ocean Dream Samudra===\n[[File:Dolphin show - ancol (jakarta, indonesia 1995) (3).jpg|thumb|right|Dolphin show]]\nOcean Dream Samudra features several animal shows, a small aquarium, and a 4D theater. The trained animal shows include a [[dolphin]] show and [[sea lion]] show. The 4D theater projects 3D image movies with sensations such as cool breezes and water sprays located inside a large building with [[Mesoamerican pyramid]] theme. On 2011 Ocean Dream Samudra will be revitalized with the budget Rp.27 billion ($3.1 million). Ocean Dream Samudra now holds the \"Under the Sea Musical Dance\" attraction at Underwater Theater.\n\n====Dolphin exhibit====\n*[[Bottlenose dolphin]]\n\n====Sea Lion exhibit====\n*[[South American sea lion]]\n\n====Sea Lion show====\n*[[Asian small-clawed otter]]\n*[[South American fur seal]]\n\n====Koi aquarium====\n*[[Koi]]\n*[[Flowerhorn cichlid]]\n\n====Rumah Pintar (Library and museum)====\n*[[Flowerhorn cichlid]]\n*[[Oscar cichlid]]\n*[[Silver arowana]] (Preserved)\n*[[Pufferfish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Bowmouth Guitarfish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Porcupinefish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Blacktip reef shark]] (Preserved)\n*[[Orange-spotted grouper]] (Preserved)\n*[[Asian small-clawed otter]] (3 pups, preserved)\n*[[Bala shark]] (Preserved)\n*[[Bottlenose dolphin]] (3 calfs, preserved)\n*[[Ribbon eel]] (Preserved)\n*[[Clown featherback]] (Preserved)\n*[[South American sea lion]] (Pup, preserved)\n*[[Coral catshark]] (Preserved)\n*[[Walking catfish]] (Preserved)\n*[[Iridescent shark]] (Preserved)\n\n====Aviary====\n*[[Sun conure]]\n*[[Scarlet macaw]]\n*[[Green winged macaw]]\n*[[Blue-and-yellow macaw]]\n*[[Yellow-crested cockatoo]]\n*[[White cockatoo]]\n*[[Javan peafowl]]\n*[[Brahminy kite]]\n*[[White-bellied sea eagle]]\n\n====Tortoise exhibit====\n*[[Asian forest tortoise]]\n\n====Duck Pond====\n*[[American Pekin]]\n*[[Swedish Blue]]\n*[[Chinese goose]] (white)\n\n====Penguin Kingdom====\n*[[Humboldt penguin]]\n*[[Blacktip reef shark]]\n*[[Coral catshark]]\n*[[Protoreaster nodosus]]\n\n====Former animals====\n*[[Hippopotamus]] (To Ming Tse) \n*[[Sun bear]]\n*[[Asian water monitor]]\n*[[Bali duck]]\n*[[Australian pelican]]\n*[[Milkfish]]\n*[[Beluga whale]]\n\n===Sea World Ancol===\n{{See also|Sea World Jakarta}} \nSeaWorld Ancol was the largest oceanarium in South East Asia at the time it was opened, in 1996, as SeaWorld Jakarta. It was owned by [[Lippo Group]] until 2014, when contract problems caused it to be owned by Jaya Ancol now. It features the acclaimed Antasena tunnel as well as the sea friends pool, main pool, alligator pool, and shark pool.<ref>http://www.seaworldindonesia.com SeaWorld Indonesia</ref> Despite its name, it is completely unaffiliated with the US-based [[SeaWorld Parks & Entertainment]] and their parks in Orlando, San Antonio, and San Diego.<ref>http://seaworldparks.com {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413191552/http://seaworldparks.com/ |date=2014-04-13 }}</ref>\n\n===Beaches===\n[[File:Festival beach Ancol Jakarta.jpg|thumb|right|Festival Beach]]\nThere are two main beaches within the resort, the Carnival and Festival beach.  British band [[Iron Maiden]] has played for the first time in Indonesia on 17 February 2011 at the Carnival Beach site, to over 25,000 strong crowd.<ref>[http://ironmaidenflight666.blogspot.com/2011/02/jakarta-setlist-final-frontier-tour.html BLOG FLIGHT 666 - IRON MAIDEN BRASIL: Jakarta: Setlist The Final Frontier Tour 2011<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Pasar Seni===\nPasar Seni is an Art Market that started over 25 years ago. .  It has become a center for handicrafts and art products. This art market has an open state, plaza, and souvenir shops. Pasar Seni has also become a center where artists would create and sell their products. Every Friday night at 8:30 pm, Pasar Seni Ancol organized the event named \"New Friday Jazz Nite\".\n\n===Executive Golf Fun===\n[[File:Arapaima gigas at sea world.JPG|thumb|right|Arapaima fish at Sea World]]\nAncol's Golf Course has recently relaunched as Executive Golf Fun. This is Indonesia\u2019s first international beach golf course with 18 holes spread over an area of 33&nbsp;hectares. The golf course has a pro-shop, an executive room, a meeting hall and restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancol.com/maps/padanggolf/padanggolf.php?action%3Dprofile |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301094330/http://www.ancol.com/maps/padanggolf/padanggolf.php?action=profile |archivedate=2008-03-01 }} Executive Golf Fun</ref>\n\n===Jaya Bowling===\nAncol Dreamland has several facilities for games and entertainment. One of these facilities is Jaya Bowling. This bowling center is the first and largest bowling center in Indonesia. Indonesia's National Bowling Training Center is in Jaya Bowling.\n\n===Allianz Eco Park===\nIt was built in 2011 by PT Global Land Development Tbk with a budget of Rp.15 billion ($1.7 million). This area  consists of 4 themes, Eco Energy, Eco Care, Eco Nature and Eco Art. It once hosted the 2013 [[World Robot Olympiad]] and the finale and result and reunion show of [[Indonesian Idol 2012]].\n\n====Pony ride====\n*[[Pony]]\n\n====Siamang Island====\n*[[Siamang]]\n*[[Koi]]\n\n====Pelican island====\n*[[Australian pelican]]\n\n====Learning Farm====\nThe farm have a hybrid between local duck and muscovy duck, named TikTok.\n*[[Javan rusa]]\n*[[Helmeted guineafowl]]\n*[[Chinese goose]] (White)\n*[[Dutch rabbit]]\n*[[American rabbit]]\n*[[Water buffalo]]\n*[[Honey bee]]\n\n====Turkey island====\n*[[Domesticated turkey]]\n\n====Parrot aviary====\n*[[Black-capped lory]]\n\n====Former animals====\n*[[Red-eared slider]]\n*[[Amboina box turtle]]\n*[[Northern cassowary]] (Moved to Fauna Land)\n*[[Domesticated pigeon]]\n\n===Fauna Land===\nFaunaland is a zoo located inside Allianz Ecopark and stands on an area of \u200b\u200bapproximately 5 hectares consisting of land and water. Faunaland carries the concept of Papua which is a fusion between the continents of Asia and Australia so as to create the beauty of flora, fauna and the cultural arts of the area. This concept presents unique and rare animals from various regions in Indonesia, especially eastern Indonesia and also countries in the world.\n\n====Leopard exhibit====\n*[[Javan leopard]]\n*[[Black panther]] (One individual only have three legs, one of its legs got trapped in pig trap)\n\n====Rare animals area====\n*[[Malayan tapir]]\n*[[Sunda porcupine]]\n\n====Petting zone====\n*[[Donkey]]\n*[[Pony]]\n*[[American Pygmy]]\n*[[Rabbit]]\n\n====Wild cat exhibit====\n*[[Asian golden cat]]\n*[[Sunda clouded leopard]]\n*[[Serval]]\n*[[Twelve-wired bird-of-paradise]]\n*[[Binturong]] (subspecies that came from Java)\n\n====Mini primate exhibits====\n*[[Spectral tarsier]]\n*[[Silvery marmoset]]\n\n====Marsupial exhibits====\n*[[Grizzled tree kangaroo]]\n*[[Banded linsang]]\n*[[Red-necked wallaby]] (Albino)\n\n====Petting zone 2====\n*[[Pony]]\n*[[Donkey]]\n\n====Cassowary exhibit====\n*[[Northern cassowary]]\n\n====White lion exhibit====\n*[[White lion]]\n\n====Tortoise exhibit====\n*[[Aldabra giant tortoise]]\n\n====Pond====\n*[[Amphilophus labiatus]]\n*[[Tilapia]]\n\n====Bird Island====\n*[[Pesquet's parrot]]\n*[[Palm cockatoo]]\n*[[Eclectus parrot]]\n*[[Papuan hornbill]]\n*[[Blue-and-yellow macaw]]\n*[[Green winged macaw]]\n*[[Lesser bird-of-paradise]]\n\n====Bird show====\n*[[Wreathed hornbill]]\n*[[Rhinoceros hornbill]]\n*[[Brahminy kite]]\n*[[Barred eagle owl]]\n*[[White-bellied sea eagle]]\n*[[Australian pelican]]\n*[[Sunda porcupine]]\n\n====Primate exhibits====\n*[[Black-spotted cuscus]]\n*[[Coconut crab]]\n*[[Proboscis monkey]]\n*[[Crab-eating macaque]] (Albino)\n*[[Siamang]] (The zoo have an albino siamang named Otong, which is the only one in the world)\n\n====Quarantined animals====\n*[[Northern lynx]]\n*[[Black-headed python]]\n*[[Common spotted cuscus]] (Albino)\n\n====Former animals====\n*[[Great grey owl]]\n*[[Australian green tree frog]]\n*[[Mandarin duck]]\n*[[Writhed hornbill]]\n*[[Knobbed hornbill]]\n*[[Lesser flamingo]]\n*[[Javan peafowl]]\n*[[Sunda porcupine]] (Albino)\n\nThe zoo planned to add [[Golden tiger]], [[Crocodile skink]], [[Northern snake-necked turtle]], [[Hyacinth macaw]], [[Sulawesi bear cuscus]], [[Silver pheasant]], [[Cream-coloured giant squirrel]], [[Snowy owl]], and [[Pig-nosed turtle]], but there is no further information.\n\n===Ancol Beach City===\nAncol Beach City is a new Lifestyle & Entertainment Center in Ancol, Jakarta. It was built by PT Wahana Agung Indonesia, a subsidiary of PT Global Land Development Tbk (now MNC Land). There'll be a Madame Tussauds wax Museum, Mata Elang International Stadium Concert Hall with a maximum capacity of 22.000, 77 culinary centre, 42 shops, etc.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120109021154/http://travel.okezone.com/read/2012/01/04/407/551584/ancol-beach-city-alternatif-gaul-anak-muda-jakarta Ancol Beach City, Alternatif Gaul Anak Muda Jakarta<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nAncol Dreamland can easily be reached by car, motorcycle, electric train (KRL), or the [[TransJakarta]] Busway.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120730173834/http://www.beritajakarta.com/2008/en/newsview.aspx?id=12533 Berita Jakarta.com]</ref> Passengers who wants to go to Ancol Dreamland by train can arrive on Kampung Bandan or Ancol Station. Because Ancol Dreamland is so large, effective transportation has been a concern. Some transportation methods around Ancol Dreamland include becak (rickshaw) and other vehicles such as train ride from the east entrance to Carnaval beach, and gondola to help tourists navigate around the area to their next destination. Passengers from Kampung Melayu, Harmoni, and Pusat Grosir Cililitan can use [[Transjakarta|Transjakarta Busway]] to go to Ancol Dreamland.\n\n===Gondola===\n[[File:Cable car Gondola Ancol Jakarta Bay City.jpg|thumb|right|Ancol Gondola]]\nThis is the latest transportation alternative in the area. The Gondola is a skylift cable car system with thirty-seven cars built along the shore of Jakarta's bay. It offers a view of the resort and the sea as well as the city.\n\n==Hotels==\n* [[Putri Duyung Cottage]] is the home of beach cottages with over 137 waterfront rooms. Putri Duyung Cottage is also one of building projects of PT Global Land Development Tbk. \n* [[Mercure Convention Centre]], formerly the Hotel Horison, is a four-star hotel that consists of a hotel tower and large mice facility. The hotel was built in the 1970s as the largest hotel at Ancol. In the 1970s, there was the Copacabana Casino, one of the three legal casinos in Jakarta that were licensed in 1967 by Governor [[Ali Sadikin]] (the others being casinos on [[Jalan M.H. Thamrin|Jalan Thamrin]] and Jalan Hayam Wuruk) in order to raise venture to help fund development of the city's infrastructure. Pressure from religious leaders eventually forced the government to ban all gambling in 1981.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015}}\n* [[Hotel Raddin Ancol]] is an Accor's [[Mercure Hotels|Mercure]] managed hotel located by the side of Dunia Fantasi.\n\n==Residential==\nAncol project also included a residential development to the east of Putri Duyung Cottage developed back in the 1970s. Some of the residential projects were the Ancol Mansion apartment complex.{{sfn|Merrillees|2015}}\n\n==Future developments==\nAncol Taman Impian is planned to be expanded mainly through land reclamation along Jakarta's bay with a land reserve of over eighty hectares. A long-term goal which includes a major expansion of the current Dunia Fantasi theme park as well as the construction of the Marina Sports Centre and Carnival Beach Club. And in this year Ancol is going to Build the Bird Park and the rumored location at Allianz Ecopark.\n\n==Accidents==\nA cement-based decorative wall of a water slide of the Atlantis Water Adventure Park collapsed due to corrosion and made a part of the wall of water slide also collapse in September 25, 2011 injuring four visitors, including a child. The Jakarta Construction Supervision and Regulation Agency said, \"There will be an audit by a consultant before the management is allowed to rebuild the collapsed structure.\" Less than 3 months previously, there was another cement structure that collapsed and in July 2011, fifteen passengers panicked when they were stuck on their seats when the Tornado thrill ride stalled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/09/25/5-injured-atlantis-water-park-accident.html |title=5 injured in Atlantis water park accident |date=September 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002153257/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/09/25/5-injured-atlantis-water-park-accident.html |archivedate=2011-10-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/at-least-2-injured-in-ancol-water-slide-collapse/467576 \n |title=At Least 2 Injured in Ancol Water Slide Collapse \n |date=September 25, 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927142409/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/home/at-least-2-injured-in-ancol-water-slide-collapse/467576 \n |archivedate=2011-09-27 \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/09/29/atlantis-be-penalized-over-accident.html |title=Atlantis to be penalized over accident |date=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n*[[Ancol]]\n*[[Jakarta]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Cited works==\n*{{cite book |last=Merrillees |first=Scott |date=2015 |title=Jakarta: Portraits of a Capital 1950-1980 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=akLWjgEACAAJ&dq=JAKARTA:+Portraits+of+a+Capital+1950-1980 |location=Jakarta |publisher=Equinox Publishing |isbn=9786028397308  |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ancol Jakarta Bay City}}\n*[http://www.ancol.com Official site]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Indonesia}}\n\n[[Category:Amusement parks in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Parks and lakes in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Animatronic attractions]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1966]]\n[[Category:Venues of the 2018 Asian Games]]\n", "name_user": "125.161.128.252", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMarsupial exhibits)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancol_Dreamland"}
{"title_page": "Saint Illtyd's Walk", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox hiking trail\n |name=Saint Illtyd\u2019s Walk\n |photo=\n |caption=\n |location=[[Wales]], [[United Kingdom hehe pp]]\n |designation=\n |length_mi=64\n |trailheads=[[Pembrey Country Park]] and [[Margam Country Park]]\n |use=[[Hiking]]\n |elev_change=\n |highest=\n\n |lowest=\n |difficulty=\n |season=\n |sights=\n |hazards=\n}}\n\n'''Saint Illtyd's Walk''' is a 103km / 64 mile long waymarked [[long distance footpath]] in South [[Wales]] running from [[Pembrey Country Park]] (OS grid ref SN 403000) west of [[Burry Port]] through rural eastern [[Carmarthenshire]] and [[Neath Port Talbot]] to end at [[Margam Country Park]] (OS grid ref SS 806862) south of [[Port Talbot]]. [[Illtud|Saint Illtyd]] (or Illtud) was a late fifth / early sixth century Welsh [[saint]].\n\n== The route ==\nThe route skirts the fringes of Burry Port, heading east to the Lliedi reservoirs then to [[Pontarddulais]]. It then turns northeast heading up via Graig Fawr onto [[Mynydd y Gwair]] then heads southeast via Bryn Mawr and Mynydd Carnllechart to the [[Swansea Canal]] north of [[Pontardawe]] following the towpath past [[Ynysmeudwy]] and [[Cilmaengwyn]]. The route then climbs east over the northern end of the [[Mynydd Marchywel]] ridge and down to cross the [[River Dulais]] at [[Crynant]]. From there it climbs steeply up through forestry to [[Sarn Helen]] which here runs along [[Hirfynydd]] and then steeply down to [[Resolven]] in the [[Vale of Neath]]. Passing [[Melincourt Falls]] it climbs again to Cefnmawr and then turns south bound for [[Cwm Afan]]. From there it runs through [[Afan Forest Park]] to the village of [[Bryn, Neath Port Talbot|Bryn]] thence through more forestry via Mynydd Bach before dropping down to Mynydd y Castell and Margam Country Park.<ref>Ordnance Survey 1>25,000 scale Explorer map sheet 165 ''Swansea/Abertawe''</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=St+Illtyd%27s+Walk]\n\n{{Long-distance footpaths in Wales}}\n\n{{coord missing|Glamorgan}}\n\n[[Category:Recreational walks in Wales]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in Wales]]\n\n{{wales-geo-stub}}\n{{UK-trail-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox hiking trail\n |name=Saint Illtyd\u2019s Walk\n |photo=\n |caption=\n |location=[[Wales]], [[United Kingdom]]\n |designation=\n |length_mi=64\n |trailheads=[[Pembrey Country Park]] and [[Margam Country Park]]\n |use=[[Hiking]]\n |elev_change=\n |highest=\n\n |lowest=\n |difficulty=\n |season=\n |sights=\n |hazards=\n}}\n\n'''Saint Illtyd's Walk''' is a 103km / 64 mile long waymarked [[long distance footpath]] in South [[Wales]] running from [[Pembrey Country Park]] (OS grid ref SN 403000) west of [[Burry Port]] through rural eastern [[Carmarthenshire]] and [[Neath Port Talbot]] to end at [[Margam Country Park]] (OS grid ref SS 806862) south of [[Port Talbot]]. [[Illtud|Saint Illtyd]] (or Illtud) was a late fifth / early sixth century Welsh [[saint]].\n\n== The route ==\nThe route skirts the fringes of Burry Port, heading east to the Lliedi reservoirs then to [[Pontarddulais]]. It then turns northeast heading up via Graig Fawr onto [[Mynydd y Gwair]] then heads southeast via Bryn Mawr and Mynydd Carnllechart to the [[Swansea Canal]] north of [[Pontardawe]] following the towpath past [[Ynysmeudwy]] and [[Cilmaengwyn]]. The route then climbs east over the northern end of the [[Mynydd Marchywel]] ridge and down to cross the [[River Dulais]] at [[Crynant]]. From there it climbs steeply up through forestry to [[Sarn Helen]] which here runs along [[Hirfynydd]] and then steeply down to [[Resolven]] in the [[Vale of Neath]]. Passing [[Melincourt Falls]] it climbs again to Cefnmawr and then turns south bound for [[Cwm Afan]]. From there it runs through [[Afan Forest Park]] to the village of [[Bryn, Neath Port Talbot|Bryn]] thence through more forestry via Mynydd Bach before dropping down to Mynydd y Castell and Margam Country Park.<ref>Ordnance Survey 1>25,000 scale Explorer map sheet 165 ''Swansea/Abertawe''</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=St+Illtyd%27s+Walk]\n\n{{Long-distance footpaths in Wales}}\n\n{{coord missing|Glamorgan}}\n\n[[Category:Recreational walks in Wales]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in Wales]]\n\n{{wales-geo-stub}}\n{{UK-trail-stub}}\n", "name_user": "174.130.228.156", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Illtyd%27s_Walk"}
