{"title_page": "Llyr Gruffydd", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox AM\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Ll\u0177r Huws Gruffydd\n|honorific-suffix = [[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|AM]]\n|image        = Llyr Gruffydd AM (27889492780).jpg\n|imagesize    = \n|alt          = \n|caption      = \n|constituency_AM = [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]]\n|assembly     = National Assembly for Wales{{!}}Welsh\n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 6 May 2011\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|9|25|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = \n|party        = [[Plaid Cymru]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|signature_alt= \n|website      = \n|footnotes    = \n}}\n'''Ll\u0177r Huws Gruffydd''', (born 25 September 1970) is a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[Plaid Cymru]] politician, and a [[National Assembly for Wales|Member of the Welsh Assembly]] for the [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]] region.<ref>[http://www.senedd.assemblywales.org/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=425 Llyr Hughes Gruffydd AM] official biography at the Welsh Assembly website</ref>\n\n==Background==\nGruffydd attended [[Bro Myrddin Welsh Comprehensive School]] and [[Aberystwyth University]]. He started his career as a youth worker, becoming Senior Development Officer with the Wales Youth Agency and the chief officer for the Council for Wales of Voluntary Youth Services.\n\nHe was elected to Carmarthen Town Council in 1995 and was mayor in 2001\u201302.\n\nHe lives near [[Ruthin]] in [[Denbighshire]] and, until his election as AM, worked as the Wales Communications Officer for the [[National Trust]]. He was previously a manager with the economic development company, Menter a Busnes.\n\n==Politics==\nFrom 1999 to 2003 Gruffydd worked as a researcher and press officer for Plaid's [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]], [[Jill Evans]] MEP and [[Eurig Wyn]] MEP. He was also national campaign co-ordinator for [[Dafydd Wigley]], in the run-up to the 1999 National Assembly elections, at which time Wigley was president of Plaid Cymru.\n\nHe was Plaid Cymru's Assembly candidate for [[Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire (Assembly constituency)|Carmarthen West & South Pembrokeshire]] in 2003 when he came within 400 votes of taking the seat from [[Christine Gwyther]] AM.\nAfter moving back to Denbighshire in 2004, Gruffydd was the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 Westminster Election]] candidate for [[Clwyd West (UK Parliament constituency)|Clwyd West]], increasing the party's vote by over 50% and securing the second biggest swing to Plaid in the country.\n\nIn the [[2011 National Assembly for Wales election]], he was returned as one of the four members of the Welsh Assembly for the North Wales region, being the first placed candidate on the Plaid Cymru list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.senedd.assemblywales.org/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?ID=46|title=Election results for North Wales - National Assembly for Wales Regional Elections 2011|publisher=[[National Assembly for Wales]]|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently the party's Shadow Minister for the Environment and Rural Affairs and is Chair of the National Assembly's Finance Committee.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20130415145540/http://www.english.plaidcymru.org/llyr-huws-gruffydd/ Llyr Huws Gruffydd], profile at the site of Plaid Cymru official site\n\n==Offices held==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Janet Ryder]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Angela Burns]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Assembly for Wales|Shadow Minister for Education, Children, Skills and Lifelong Learning]]|years= 2016 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Welsh AMs}}\n{{Plaid Cymru}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gruffydd, Llyr Huws}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru Members of the National Assembly for Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 2011\u20132016]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ruthin]]\n[[Category:Welsh-speaking politicians]]\n\n\n{{Wales-AM-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox AM\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Ll\u0177r Huws Gruffydd\n|honorific-suffix = [[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|AM]]\n|image        = Llyr Gruffydd AM (27889492780).jpg\n|imagesize    = \n|alt          = \n|caption      = \n|constituency_AM = [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]]\n|assembly     = National Assembly for Wales{{!}}Welsh\n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 6 May 2011\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|9|25|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = \n|party        = [[Plaid Cymru]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|signature_alt= \n|website      = \n|footnotes    = \n}}\n'''Ll\u0177r Huws Gruffydd''', (born 25 September 1970) is a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[Plaid Cymru]] politician, and a [[National Assembly for Wales|Member of the Welsh Assembly]] for the [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]] region.<ref>[http://www.senedd.assemblywales.org/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=425 Llyr Hughes Gruffydd AM] official biography at the Welsh Assembly website</ref>\n\n==Background==\nGruffydd attended [[Bro Myrddin Welsh Comprehensive School]] and [[Aberystwyth University]]. He started his career as a youth worker, becoming Senior Development Officer with the Wales Youth Agency and the chief officer for the Council for Wales of Voluntary Youth Services.\n\nHe was elected to Carmarthen Town Council in 1995 and was Mayor in 2001\u201302.\n\nHe lives near [[Ruthin]] in [[Denbighshire]] and, until his election as AM, worked as the Wales Communications Officer for the [[National Trust]]. He was previously a manager with the economic development company, Menter a Busnes.\n\n==Politics==\nFrom 1999 to 2003 Gruffydd worked as a researcher and press officer for Plaid's [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]], [[Jill Evans]] MEP and [[Eurig Wyn]] MEP. He was also national campaign co-ordinator for [[Dafydd Wigley]], in the run-up to the 1999 National Assembly elections, at which time Wigley was President of Plaid Cymru .\n\nHe was Plaid Cymru's Assembly candidate for [[Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire (Assembly constituency)|Carmarthen West & South Pembrokeshire]] in 2003 when he came within 400 votes of taking the seat from [[Christine Gwyther]] AM.\nAfter moving back to Denbighshire in 2004, Gruffydd was the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 Westminster Election]] candidate for [[Clwyd West (UK Parliament constituency)|Clwyd West]], increasing the party's vote by over 50% and securing the second biggest swing to Plaid in the country.\n\nIn the [[2011 National Assembly for Wales election]], he was returned as one of the four members of the Welsh Assembly for the North Wales region, being the first placed candidate on the Plaid Cymru list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.senedd.assemblywales.org/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?ID=46|title=Election results for North Wales - National Assembly for Wales Regional Elections 2011|publisher=[[National Assembly for Wales]]|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently the party's Shadow Minister for the Environment and Rural Affairs and is Chair of the National Assembly's Finance Committee.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20130415145540/http://www.english.plaidcymru.org/llyr-huws-gruffydd/ Llyr Huws Gruffydd], profile at the site of Plaid Cymru official site\n\n==Offices held==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Janet Ryder]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Angela Burns]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Assembly for Wales|Shadow Minister for Education, Children, Skills and Lifelong Learning]]|years= 2016 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Welsh AMs}}\n{{Plaid Cymru}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gruffydd, Llyr Huws}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru Members of the National Assembly for Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 2011\u20132016]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ruthin]]\n[[Category:Welsh-speaking politicians]]\n\n\n{{Wales-AM-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Llyr_Gruffydd"}
